04206nam a22006135i 9780292761223DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927612237 a10.7560/7612162doi  a(DE-B1597)586951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1998.3.R633bA64 2014eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4302/330922231 aAldama, Frederick Luis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cinema of Robert Rodriguez /cFrederick Luis Aldama. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (187 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword: A Teaser before the Show by Charles Ramírez Berg -- tAcknowledgments -- tArt and Industry: The Films of Robert Rodriguez -- tGood, Bad, Ugly . . . and Beautiful -- tRegenerative Aesthetics of Degenerate Genres -- tFamilia Redefined, Chocolate Rivers, Rainbow Rocks, Dreamscapes, and S’mores -- tTour de Noir Comic-Book Film -- tOtherworldly Mutants, Bandidas, Borderland Vigilantes . . . Fight Back -- tIt’s a Wrap -- tInterview with Robert Rodriguez -- tFilmography -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRobert Rodriguez stands alone as the most successful U.S. Latino filmmaker today, whose work has single-handedly brought U.S. Latino filmmaking into the mainstream of twenty-first-century global cinema. Rodriguez is a prolific (eighteen films in twenty-one years) and all-encompassing filmmaker who has scripted, directed, shot, edited, and scored nearly all his films since his first breakout success, El Mariachi, in 1992. With new films constantly coming out and the launch of his El Rey Network television channel, he receives unceasing coverage in the entertainment media, but systematic scholarly study of Rodriguez’s films is only just beginning. The Cinema of Robert Rodriguez offers the first extended investigation of this important filmmaker’s art. Accessibly written for fans as well as scholars, it addresses all of Rodriguez’s feature films through Spy Kids 4 and Machete Kills, and his filmmaking process from initial inspiration, to script, to film (with its myriad visual and auditory elements and choices), to final product, to (usually) critical and commercial success. In addition to his close analysis of Rodriguez’s work, Frederick Luis Aldama presents an original interview with the filmmaker, in which they discuss his career and his relationship to the film industry. This entertaining and much-needed scholarly overview of Rodriguez’s work shines new light on several key topics, including the filmmaker’s creative, low-cost, efficient approach to filmmaking; the acceptance of Latino films and filmmakers in mainstream cinema; and the consumption and reception of film in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aBerg, Charles Ramírez.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76121640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292761223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292761223/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK